value.value: A procedure in which a single dose of a pharmalogical substance is administered, generally via injection, over a short period of time.
A carcinoma arising from the intrahepatic bile ducts, hepatic ducts, common bile duct, cystic duct, or gallbladder.
The reemergence of a carcinoma arising from any part of the biliary tract after a period of remission.

A supraglottic airway device that is composed of an airway tube that connects to an inflatable elliptical mask on the distal end which is inserted through the patient's mouth, down the trachea, and inflated to form an airtight seal on top the glottis.
Having reached a completed state of growth and development.
An indication that an individual's growth plates are fused and that bone growth has ceased.
An indication that an individual's growth plates are open and that bone growth is likely to continue.
An indication of skeletal growth potential based on skeletal maturity indicators, such as radiologic imaging of growth plates.
A basal cell carcinoma that has spread from its original site of growth to another anatomic site and is not amenable to surgical resection.

label.value: Locally Advanced Unresectable Basal Cell Carcinoma

value.value: A basal cell carcinoma that has spread from its original site of growth to nearby tissues or lymph nodes and is not amenable to surgical resection.
Treatment that is given after initial therapy to kill any remaining cancer cells.

label.value: Maternally Derived Graft Versus Host Disease

value.value: Graft versus host disease (GVHD) that occurs in an infant as the result of engraftment of maternal lymphocytes, resulting from in utero maternal-fetal cellular trafficking.

A humanized, hybridoma monoclonal antibody against the poliovirus receptor-related immunoglobulin (PVRIG; PVR Related Immunoglobulin Domain Containing Protein; CD112R), with potential immune checkpoint inhibitory and antineoplastic activities. Upon administration, anti-PVRIG monoclonal antibody COM701 targets and binds to PVRIG expressed on cytotoxic T-lymphocytes (CTLs) and natural killer (NK) cells within the tumor microenvironment (TME). This blocks the interaction of PVRIG with its ligand nectin cell adhesion molecule 2 (poliovirus receptor-related 2; PVRL2; CD112), which is overexpressed on a variety of tumor cell types. Inhibiting the activation of PVRIG, abrogates the PVRIG-induced inhibition of T-lymphocyte and NK cell activation. This activates CTLs and NK cells, enhances anti-tumor responses and immune-mediated tumor cell killing, and inhibits tumor cell proliferation. PVRIG, a member of the B7/CD28 family and immune checkpoint receptor that, upon activation, negatively regulates the activation of various immune cells. It plays a key role in immunosuppression.

A maleimide-based, small molecule inhibitor of glycogen synthase kinase-3 (GSK-3; serine/threonine-protein kinase GSK3) with potential antineoplastic activity. Upon intravenous administration, elraglusib binds to and competitively inhibits GSK-3, which may lead to downregulation of nuclear factor kappa B (NF-kappaB) and decreased expression of NF-kappaB target genes including cyclin D1, B-cell lymphoma 2 (Bcl-2), anti-apoptotic protein XIAP, and B-cell lymphoma extra-large (Bcl-XL). This may inhibit NF-kappaB-mediated survival and chemoresistance in certain tumor types. GSK-3, a constitutively active serine/threonine kinase that plays a role in numerous pathways involved in protein synthesis, cellular proliferation, differentiation, and metabolism, is aberrantly overexpressed in certain tumor types and may promote tumor cell survival and resistance to chemotherapy and radiotherapy.
A malignant neoplasm that is associated with human papillomavirus infection and has spread from its original site of growth to another anatomic site.
Any agent that inhibits interleukin-2-inducible kinase (ITK).

label.value: Prior Radiation Therapy of Affected Breast

value.value: An indication that an individual has previously received radiation treatment of their currently affected breast.

label.value: Prior Systemic Chemotherapy for Current Cancer

value.value: An indication that an individual has previously received systemic chemotherapy for their current malignancy.

label.value: Prior Systemic Therapy for Current Cancer

value.value: An indication that an individual has previously received systemic therapy for their current malignancy.
This gene plays a role in the inhibition of T-cell activation and proliferation.

Human PVRIG wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 7q22.1 and is approximately 5 kb in length. This allele, which encodes transmembrane protein PVRIG, may be involved in immune checkpoint signaling.

A saturated derivative of sphingosine. As an inhibitor of protein kinase C (PKC), safingol competitively binds to the regulatory phorbol-binding domain of PKC, a kinase involved in tumorigenesis. This agent has been shown to act synergistically with other chemotherapeutic agents and may potentiate chemotherapy drug-induced apoptosis in vitro and in vivo.
The removal of a tissue sample using a needle with a relatively large diameter, for microscopic examination.
An indication that an individual has previously received therapy for their current malignancy.
An infection with human immunodeficiency virus that responds to therapy.

label.value: Radiation to Greater than 25 Percent of Bone Marrow

value.value: Bone marrow irradiation targeting greater than 25 percent of the total bone marrow.
Transmembrane protein PVRIG (326 aa, ~34 kDa) is encoded by the human PVRIG gene. This protein plays a role in the inhibition of T-cell-mediated immunity.
Any agent that inhibits the histone lysine methyltransferase EZH2.

A finding indicating the development of a tumor in a patient with a history of a previously diagnosed tumor with a different histopathologic profile in another anatomic site as compared to the most recent one.
The identifier assigned to a case within the National Cancer Institute's Clinical Proteomic Tumor Analysis Consortium (CPTAC).
An identifier assigned to a tissue source site.
Any kind of illness or circumstance which requires medical monitoring.
A drug therapy that is used to destroy cancer cells.
Data pertinent to a newly discovered tumor.

label.value: Is there a History of Treatment

value.value: A question about whether there is a known history of treatments.
The source providing the medical history.
The first diagnosis of the individual's condition.
The date of the last radiation treatment, chemotherapy, molecular targeted therapy, or immunotherapy treatment.
The date of the last administration of chemotherapy.
A format of a date in time, with the month followed by the date followed by the year.

label.value: Medical Record Documentation about this History of Cancer Treatment

value.value: The documentation in the medical record regarding previous treatment for cancer.
The current medications an individual is taking.
The date of the last administration of the substance of interest.
The amount of any substance administered over a specific period of time.

label.value: Alcohol Consumption Equal to or Less than 2 Drinks per Day for Men and 1 Drink or Less per Day for Women

value.value: Alcohol consumption equal to or less than two drinks per day for men and one drink or less per day for women.

label.value: Alcohol Consumption More than 2 Drinks per Day for Men and More than 1 Drink per Day for Women

value.value: Alcohol consumption more than two drinks per day for men and more than one drink per day for women.

label.value: Current non-drinker with Past Alcohol Consumption

value.value: An indication that an individual has consumed alcohol in the past, but is currently a non-drinker.
An indication that the alcohol use history of an individual is unavailable.

label.value: Number of Years When Consumed More than 2 Drinks per Day for Men and More than 1 Drink per Day for Women

value.value: The number of years an individual has consumed more than 2 drinks per day for men and more than 1 drink per day for women.
